Settings.

The settings screen — labeled preferences when you open it — is where you tune how the game sounds, plays, and behaves. Everything you change here is remembered between sessions once you save it. This topic walks through every option, grouped the way the screen groups them, so you know what each one does before you flip it.

Where to find it and how it's organized.

Open the preferences menu from the main menu. You can also open it while you're in a map, in two ways: by typing the /preffs command (or its short form /pf), or by stepping into a menu zone that's set to the settings menu. The screen is split into tabs you move between with your arrows: General, Game, Keyboard, and Speech. Two of those tabs — General and Keyboard — are only available from the main menu; when you open it during play, only the Game and Speech tabs appear, since theme, device, and key-binding changes are meant to be made outside a map. At the bottom of every tab sit the save and cancel buttons, covered at the end.

The General tab.

The General tab holds the one-time setup choices — themes, audio device, and the default map owner. It is only available from the main menu. Its options are the following:

Select character theme. Choose which character you play as. The character sets the player's voice and the body sounds you hear — footsteps, attacks, hurt and death cues, map-loading sounds — along with the stats you start a map with. The button shows the character currently chosen. See the characters topic for what the different characters offer.
Select keyboard theme. Choose the set of sounds played as you type and move through text fields, so keyboard input has the feel you prefer. The button shows the current choice.
Select menu theme. Choose the set of sounds menus play as you move through and select items. The button shows the current choice.

Select sound device. Choose which audio output device the game plays through, picked from a list of the devices on your system. Use this to send the game's sound to a specific headset or speaker.

Set default owner for new maps. Set the name that's filled in as the owner whenever you create a new map, so you don't have to type it every time. The button shows the name currently set. See the maps topic for what map ownership means.

Reset settings. Restore every setting to its default. It asks you to confirm first, then resets everything and restarts the game.

The Game tab.

The Game tab holds the on-and-off switches that shape how maps and menus behave. Each one is a checkbox you tick to turn on or untick to turn off. The options are the following:

Enable checking for game updates at startup. When on, the game checks for a newer version each time it launches and tells you if one is available.

Enable auto running in maps. When on, the player moves at running speed by default, so you cover ground quickly without holding the run key.
Enable auto jumping in maps. When on, holding the jump key makes the player keep jumping for as long as it's held; when off, each jump takes a separate press.

Enable global volume fading. When on, sound fades smoothly in and out during transitions — changing maps, stepping into a menu, leaving a map — instead of cutting off abruptly.

Enable bumping into walls repeatedly. When on, walking into a wall plays its bump sound every step you push against it; when off, the bump plays once and stays quiet until you move away and come back.
Enable turning on the spot for 2d maps. In 2d maps, when on, the first press of a movement direction turns the player to face that way instead of stepping, so you change facing in place before walking.

Enable auditory beeps when loading maps. When on, the loading screen plays a rising series of beeps that track how far the load has gotten.
Enable indicator sounds when loading maps. When on, the loading screen plays its sound cues — a start sound, a looping sound while it works, and a finish sound.

Enable clearing entities after dying on a map. Controls how a map resets when you die. When on, the map's objects are cleared and reset in place for a quick restart; when off, the whole map is reloaded from its file after each death.

Enable global HRTF support. When on, spatial audio uses head-related processing for more precise placement of sounds around your head. Turn it off if you prefer the plainer, less processed sound.

Enable wrapping in menus. When on, moving past the last item in a menu loops back to the first, and moving up from the first jumps to the last.
Enable first letter navigation in menus. When on, pressing a letter key in a menu jumps to the next item beginning with that letter.
Enable position information in menus. When on, menus tell you each item's position as you move, such as where it falls in the list and how many items there are.
Enable side scrolling in menus. When on, menu sounds pan from left to right according to how far down the list the highlighted item sits, so you can hear roughly where you are.

Ask to exit when pressing escape. When on, pressing escape to leave asks you to confirm before quitting, so you don't exit by accident.

The Keyboard tab.

The Keyboard tab is where you manage the keys that control the game. It is only available from the main menu. Its options are the following:

Rebind keyboard controls. Open the rebinding screen, where you can add, edit, or remove the key bound to any action; the game captures the key you press, and asks you to confirm before removing a binding. See the controls topic for what every action does and for editing your bindings by hand.
View current keyboard bindings. Open a read-only list of every action and the key it's currently bound to, for quick reference.

The Speech tab.

The Speech tab controls the text-to-speech voice the game reads with. Its options are the following:

Configure voice. Open the voice setup screen, described below, where you choose the voice and adjust how it sounds.
Preview voice. Hear a short test phrase spoken with your current voice settings, so you can check them by ear.

Configuring the voice.

Configure voice opens a separate screen for setting up the text-to-speech voice. As you adjust its controls the voice updates so you can hear each change as you make it, and the screen's own save and cancel buttons decide whether the changes stick — cancel puts the voice back exactly as it was when you opened it. The screen holds the following:

Use screen reader when available (checkbox). When checked, the game speaks through your computer's screen reader whenever one is running, and uses its own voice only when no screen reader is found. Uncheck it to always use the game's own voice even with a screen reader open.
Voice. Choose which of the text-to-speech voices installed on your system the game reads with.

Rate. How fast the voice speaks, from -10 at the slowest up to 10 at the fastest.
Pitch. How high or low the voice sounds, from -10 at the deepest up to 10 at the highest.
Volume. How loud the voice is, from 0 at silent up to 100 at full.

Save settings. Keep the voice changes you made and close the screen.
Cancel. Close without keeping the changes, restoring the voice to how it sounded when you opened the screen.

Saving and canceling.

At the bottom of every tab are two buttons. Save settings writes your changes and keeps them for the next time you launch. Cancel closes the screen without saving, so your changes won't be remembered next launch; pressing escape does the same as cancel.
